-- Irish, Spanish Bonds Stay Higher; Trichet Sees Buying Need `Diminishing'
-- Paul Dobson
-- 2010-07-08T13:04:07Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-08/irish-spanish-bonds-stay-higher-trichet-sees-buying-need-diminishing-.html

          
          
             Irish and Spanish 10-year government
bonds stayed higher as European Central Bank President Jean-
Claude Trichet said the need to buy government bonds may be
“diminishing.”  
 The Irish 10-year yield was two basis points lower at 5.33
percent as of 1:59 p.m. in London. The Spanish yield was also
two basis points lower at 4.65 percent, while the Portuguese 10-
year bond yield was little changed at 5.47 percent.  
 Greek 10-year bonds fell, with the yield rising 10 basis
points to 10.37 percent.  
 The German 10-year yield rose three basis points to 2.63
percent.  
